The best way to do this should be by using ListView.builder.
To use ListView.builder, you have to create an instance of it by calling its constructor using new , it takes multiple parameters.
Assume that we have a global list like this in our application

    List&lt;String&gt; litems = [&quot;1&quot;,&quot;2&quot;,&quot;Third&quot;,&quot;4&quot;];

Using LIstView.builder, the code for the same shall look like this

    body: new ListView.builder
      (
        itemCount: litems.length,
        itemBuilder: (BuildContext ctxt, int index) {
         return new Text(litems[index]);
        }
      )
In here, the in-place callback function shall be called 4 times and each call will generate a Text Widget which shall be displayed in the body.

You can also write a separate function which can be called from itemBuilder as

    // A Separate Function called from itemBuilder
    Widget buildBody(BuildContext ctxt, int index) {
      return new Text(litems[index]);
    }
    body: new ListView.builder
    (
      itemCount: litems.length,
      itemBuilder: (BuildContext ctxt, int index) =&gt; 
    buildBody(ctxt, index)
    ),

In both cases, the output will look the same. 
You can also use ListView.builder(..) in Stateless Widgets if you want to display dynamic (different) contents every time the widget is loaded within an application. With Stateful widgets, it can change the contents of the screen dynamically.
I hope this helps

